          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">The Horn of Africa deal</h2>
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopolitics.world/email/images/gp-dec-13-1.jpg" alt="The Horn of Africa deal" href="https://www.geopolitics.world" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Ethiopia and Somalia agreed to <a href="https://www.dw.com/en/ethiopia-somalia-reach-compromise-to-end-feud-turkey-says/a-71029613" target="_blank">resolve</a> a tense year-long dispute rooted in Ethiopia’s controversial <a href="https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-67861390" target="_blank">January 2024 deal</a> with Somaliland. Ethiopia reportedly negotiated to lease a coastal stretch for a port and military base in exchange for recognition of Somaliland’s independence. This move outraged Somalia, which viewed it as a violation of its sovereignty.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Turkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan brokered this agreement. He mediated separate meetings with Somali President Hassan Sheikh Mohamud and Ethiopian Prime Minister Abiy Ahmed. Ethiopia and Somalia agreed to have “technical talks” to address the dispute. The discussions are likely to start around February 2025. They have a four-month deadline to ensure Ethiopia’s access to the sea. The joint declaration underlined <a href="https://apnews.com/article/turkey-somalia-ethiopia-joint-declaration-296b4f3e4e38a92f489b854a8b4e7ccd" target="_blank">mutual benefits</a>, with plans to finalize commercial arrangements granting Ethiopia secure and sustainable sea access under Somalia’s sovereignty. This is a step towards a new beginning for the Horn of Africa.​</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>


